fields.name: alpha
fields.desc:
The fraction of this color that should be applied to the pixel. That is,
the final pixel color is defined by the equation:

  pixel color = alpha * (this color) + (1.0 - alpha) * (background color)

This means that a value of 1.0 corresponds to a solid color, whereas
a value of 0.0 corresponds to a completely transparent color. This
uses a wrapper message rather than a simple float scalar so that it is
possible to distinguish between a default value and the value being unset.
If omitted, this color object is to be rendered as a solid color
(as if the alpha value had been explicitly given with a value of 1.0).

schemas.name: GridRange
schemas.desc:
A range on a sheet.
All indexes are zero-based.
Indexes are half open, e.g the start index is inclusive
and the end index is exclusive -- [start_index, end_index).
Missing indexes indicate the range is unbounded on that side.

For example, if `"Sheet1"` is sheet ID 0, then:

  `Sheet1!A1:A1 == sheet_id: 0,
                  start_row_index: 0, end_row_index: 1,
                  start_column_index: 0, end_column_index: 1`

  `Sheet1!A3:B4 == sheet_id: 0,
                  start_row_index: 2, end_row_index: 4,
                  start_column_index: 0, end_column_index: 2`

  `Sheet1!A:B == sheet_id: 0,
                start_column_index: 0, end_column_index: 2`

  `Sheet1!A5:B == sheet_id: 0,
                 start_row_index: 4,
                 start_column_index: 0, end_column_index: 2`

  `Sheet1 == sheet_id:0`

The start index must always be less than or equal to the end index.
If the start index equals the end index, then the range is empty.
Empty ranges are typically not meaningful and are usually rendered in the
UI as `#REF!`.

fields.name: startColumnIndex
fields.desc: The start column (inclusive) of the range, or not set if unbounded.

fields.name: sheetId
fields.desc: The sheet this range is on.

fields.name: endRowIndex
fields.desc: The end row (exclusive) of the range, or not set if unbounded.

fields.name: endColumnIndex
fields.desc: The end column (exclusive) of the range, or not set if unbounded.

fields.name: startRowIndex
fields.desc: The start row (inclusive) of the range, or not set if unbounded.

enum.name: SERIAL_NUMBER
enum.desc:
Instructs date, time, datetime, and duration fields to be output
as doubles in "serial number" format, as popularized by Lotus 1-2-3.
The whole number portion of the value (left of the decimal) counts
the days since December 30th 1899. The fractional portion (right of
the decimal) counts the time as a fraction of the day. For example,
January 1st 1900 at noon would be 2.5, 2 because it's 2 days after
December 30st 1899, and .5 because noon is half a day.  February 1st
1900 at 3pm would be 33.625. This correctly treats the year 1900 as
not a leap year.

enum.name: FORMATTED_STRING
enum.desc:

not the requesting user's locale.

then `A2` would return `"$1.23"`.

enum.name: UNFORMATTED_VALUE

For example, if `A1` is `1.23` and `A2` is `=A1` and formatted as currency,

enum.name: FORMULA

For example, if `A1` is `1.23` and `A2` is `=A1` and formatted as currency,

fields.name: autoRecalc
fields.desc: The amount of time to wait before volatile functions are recalculated.

enum.name: RECALCULATION_INTERVAL_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Default value. This value must not be used.

enum.name: ON_CHANGE
enum.desc: Volatile functions are updated on every change.

enum.name: MINUTE
enum.desc: Volatile functions are updated on every change and every minute.

enum.desc: Volatile functions are updated on every change and hourly.

fields.name: defaultFormat
fields.desc:
The default format of all cells in the spreadsheet.
CellData.effectiveFormat will not be set if the
cell's format is equal to this default format.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: timeZone
fields.desc:
The time zone of the spreadsheet, in CLDR format such as
`America/New_York`. If the time zone isn't recognized, this may
be a custom time zone such as `GMT-07:00`.

fields.name: title
fields.desc: The title of the spreadsheet.

fields.name: locale
fields.desc:
The locale of the spreadsheet in one of the following formats:

* an ISO 639-1 language code such as `en`

* an ISO 639-2 language code such as `fil`, if no 639-1 code exists

* a combination of the ISO language code and country code, such as `en_US`

fields.name: iterativeCalculationSettings
fields.desc:
Determines whether and how circular references are resolved with iterative
calculation.  Absence of this field means that circular references will
result in calculation errors.

schemas.name: TextRotation
schemas.desc: The rotation applied to text in a cell.

fields.name: angle
fields.desc:
The angle between the standard orientation and the desired orientation.
Measured in degrees. Valid values are between -90 and 90. Positive
angles are angled upwards, negative are angled downwards.

Note: For LTR text direction positive angles are in the counterclockwise
direction, whereas for RTL they are in the clockwise direction

fields.name: vertical
fields.desc:
If true, text reads top to bottom, but the orientation of individual
characters is unchanged.
For example:

    | V |
    | e |
    | r |
    | t |
    | i |
    | c |
    | a |

schemas.name: ConditionalFormatRule

schemas.desc:
A condition that can evaluate to true or false.
BooleanConditions are used by conditional formatting,
data validation, and the criteria in filters.

fields.name: type
fields.desc: The type of condition.

enum.name: CONDITION_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: The default value, do not use.

enum.name: NUMBER_GREATER
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be greater than the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_GREATER_THAN_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be greater than or equal to the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_LESS
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be less than the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_LESS_THAN_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be less than or equal to the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be equal to the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_NOT_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be not equal to the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: NUMBER_BETWEEN
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be between the two condition values.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires exactly two ConditionValues.

enum.name: NUMBER_NOT_BETWEEN
enum.desc:
The cell's value must not be between the two condition values.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires exactly two ConditionValues.

enum.name: TEXT_CONTAINS
enum.desc:
The cell's value must contain the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: TEXT_NOT_CONTAINS
enum.desc:
The cell's value must not contain the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: TEXT_STARTS_WITH
enum.desc:
The cell's value must start with the condition's value.
Supported by conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: TEXT_ENDS_WITH
enum.desc:
The cell's value must end with the condition's value.
Supported by conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: TEXT_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be exactly the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: TEXT_IS_EMAIL
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be a valid email address.
Supported by data validation.
Requires no ConditionValues.

enum.name: TEXT_IS_URL
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be a valid URL.
Supported by data validation.
Requires no ConditionValues.

enum.name: DATE_EQ
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be the same date as the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

enum.name: DATE_BEFORE
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be before the date of the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue
that may be a relative date.

enum.name: DATE_AFTER
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be after the date of the condition's value.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue
that may be a relative date.

enum.name: DATE_ON_OR_BEFORE
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be on or before the date of the condition's value.
Supported by data validation.
Requires a single ConditionValue
that may be a relative date.

enum.name: DATE_ON_OR_AFTER
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be on or after the date of the condition's value.
Supported by data validation.
Requires a single ConditionValue
that may be a relative date.

enum.name: DATE_BETWEEN
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be between the dates of the two condition values.
Supported by data validation.
Requires exactly two ConditionValues.

enum.name: DATE_NOT_BETWEEN
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be outside the dates of the two condition values.
Supported by data validation.
Requires exactly two ConditionValues.

enum.name: DATE_IS_VALID
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be a date.
Supported by data validation.
Requires no ConditionValues.

enum.name: ONE_OF_RANGE
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be listed in the grid in condition value's range.
Supported by data validation.
Requires a single ConditionValue,
and the value must be a valid range in A1 notation.

enum.name: ONE_OF_LIST
enum.desc:
The cell's value must in the list of condition values.
Supported by data validation.
Supports any number of condition values,
one per item in the list.
Formulas are not supported in the values.

enum.name: BLANK
enum.desc:
The cell's value must be empty.
Supported by conditional formatting and filters.
Requires no ConditionValues.

enum.name: NOT_BLANK
enum.desc:
The cell's value must not be empty.
Supported by conditional formatting and filters.
Requires no ConditionValues.

enum.name: CUSTOM_FORMULA
enum.desc:
The condition's formula must evaluate to true.
Supported by data validation, conditional formatting and filters.
Requires a single ConditionValue.

The values of the condition. The number of supported values depends

fields.name: destinationIndex
fields.desc:
The zero-based start index of where to move the source data to,
based on the coordinates *before* the source data is removed
from the grid.  Existing data will be shifted down or right
(depending on the dimension) to make room for the moved dimensions.
The source dimensions are removed from the grid, so the
the data may end up in a different index than specified.

For example, given `A1..A5` of `0, 1, 2, 3, 4` and wanting to move
`"1"` and `"2"` to between `"3"` and `"4"`, the source would be
`ROWS [1..3)`,and the destination index would be `"4"`
(the zero-based index of row 5).
The end result would be `A1..A5` of `0, 3, 1, 2, 4`.

methods.name: get
methods.desc:
Returns the spreadsheet at the given ID.
The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID.

By default, data within grids will not be returned.
You can include grid data one of two ways:

* Specify a field mask listing your desired fields using the `fields` URL
parameter in HTTP

* Set the includeGridData
URL parameter to true.  If a field mask is set, the `includeGridData`
parameter is ignored

For large spreadsheets, it is recommended to retrieve only the specific
fields of the spreadsheet that you want.

To retrieve only subsets of the spreadsheet, use the
ranges URL parameter.
Multiple ranges can be specified.  Limiting the range will
return only the portions of the spreadsheet that intersect the requested
ranges. Ranges are specified using A1 notation.

optinalQueryParams.name: ranges
optinalQueryParams.desc: The ranges to retrieve from the spreadsheet.

optinalQueryParams.name: includeGridData
optinalQueryParams.desc:
True if grid data should be returned.
This parameter is ignored if a field mask was set in the request.

methods.name: create
methods.desc: Creates a spreadsheet, returning the newly created spreadsheet.

methods.name: batchUpdate
methods.desc:
Applies one or more updates to the spreadsheet.

Each request is validated before
being applied. If any request is not valid then the entire request will
fail and nothing will be applied.

Some requests have replies to
give you some information about how
they are applied. The replies will mirror the requests.  For example,
if you applied 4 updates and the 3rd one had a reply, then the
response will have 2 empty replies, the actual reply, and another empty
reply, in that order.

Due to the collaborative nature of spreadsheets, it is not guaranteed that
the spreadsheet will reflect exactly your changes after this completes,
however it is guaranteed that the updates in the request will be
applied together atomically. Your changes may be altered with respect to
collaborator changes. If there are no collaborators, the spreadsheet
should reflect your changes.

pathParams.name: spreadsheetId
pathParams.desc: The spreadsheet to apply the updates to.

methods.name: batchUpdate
methods.desc:
Sets values in one or more ranges of a spreadsheet.
The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID,
a valueInputOption, and one or more
ValueRanges.

pathParams.name: spreadsheetId

methods.name: batchGet
methods.desc:
Returns one or more ranges of values from a spreadsheet.
The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID and one or more ranges.

pathParams.name: spreadsheetId
pathParams.desc: The ID of the spreadsheet to retrieve data from.

optinalQueryParams.name: ranges
optinalQueryParams.desc: The A1 notation of the values to retrieve.

optinalQueryParams.name: majorDimension
optinalQueryParams.desc:
The major dimension that results should use.

For example, if the spreadsheet data is: `A1=1,B1=2,A2=3,B2=4`,
then requesting `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=ROWS` will return
`[[1,2],[3,4]]`,
whereas requesting `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=COLUMNS` will return
`[[1,3],[2,4]]`.

optinalQueryParams.name: valueRenderOption
optinalQueryParams.desc:
How values should be represented in the output.
The default render option is ValueRenderOption.FORMATTED_VALUE.

optinalQueryParams.name: dateTimeRenderOption
optinalQueryParams.desc:
How dates, times, and durations should be represented in the output.
This is ignored if value_render_option is
FORMATTED_VALUE.
The default dateTime render option is [DateTimeRenderOption.SERIAL_NUMBER].

methods.name: append
methods.desc:
Appends values to a spreadsheet. The input range is used to search for
existing data and find a "table" within that range. Values will be
appended to the next row of the table, starting with the first column of
the table. See the
[guide](/sheets/api/guides/values#appending_values)
and
[sample code](/sheets/api/samples/writing#append_values)
for specific details of how tables are detected and data is appended.

The caller must specify the spreadsheet ID, range, and
a valueInputOption.  The `valueInputOption` only
controls how the input data will be added to the sheet (column-wise or
row-wise), it does not influence what cell the data starts being written
to.

pathParams.name: spreadsheetId
pathParams.desc: The ID of the spreadsheet to update.

pathParams.name: range
pathParams.desc:
The A1 notation of a range to search for a logical table of data.
Values will be appended after the last row of the table.

optinalQueryParams.name: insertDataOption
optinalQueryParams.desc: How the input data should be inserted.

optinalQueryParams.name: valueInputOption
optinalQueryParams.desc: How the input data should be interpreted.

optinalQueryParams.name: responseDateTimeRenderOption
optinalQueryParams.desc:
Determines how dates, times, and durations in the response should be
rendered. This is ignored if response_value_render_option is
FORMATTED_VALUE.
The default dateTime render option is [DateTimeRenderOption.SERIAL_NUMBER].

optinalQueryParams.name: includeValuesInResponse

Determines if the update response should include the values
of the cells that were appended. By default, responses
do not include the updated values.

optinalQueryParams.name: responseValueRenderOption
optinalQueryParams.desc:
Determines how values in the response should be rendered.
The default render option is ValueRenderOption.FORMATTED_VALUE.
